 agency and the creative ways in which they take control of their lives in often difficult circumstances. Based on extensive ethnographic fieldwork and interviews, the author offers a valuable dual comparison between two Southern European countries on the one hand and between two migrant groups, one Christian and one Muslim, on the other, thus bringing to light unique detailed data on migration decision-making, settlement and on the multiple ways in which different women cope with the consequences of their transnational lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aFamilieszItalyzBologna. 0aFamilieszSpainzBarcelona. 0aFilipinoszItalyzBolognaxSocial conditions. 0aFilipinoszSpainzBarcelonaxSocial conditions. 0aMoroccanszItalyzBolognaxSocial conditions. 0aMoroccanszSpainzBarcelonaxSocial conditions. 0aWomen immigrantszEurope, SouthernvCase studies. 0aWomen immigrantszItalyzBologna. 0aWomen immigrantszSpainzBarcelona. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184545805840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781845458058423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781845458058/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK